{
  "project": "fixture-shop",
  "title": "HMAC Webhook Signature Verification in verify.php",
  "slug": "hmac-webhook-signature-verification",
  "date": "2026-07-17",
  "depth": "intro",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "name": "HMAC Signature Verification",
      "definition": "A security technique where a receiver recomputes a keyed hash (HMAC) over a message using a shared secret and compares it to a hash sent by the sender, confirming both that the message was not tampered with and that the sender holds the secret."
    },
    {
      "name": "Constant-Time Comparison",
      "definition": "A string comparison method that always takes the same amount of time regardless of where two values differ, preventing timing attacks where an attacker could deduce the correct value byte by byte by measuring how long comparisons take."
    }
  ],
  "files": ["src/verify.php"],
  "commit": "1c6b2f2",
  "sources": [],
  "lesson": "The `verify()` function in `src/verify.php` decides whether an incoming webhook really came from the payment gateway. It recomputes an [[fixture-shop/_glossary#HMAC Signature Verification|HMAC-SHA256 signature]] over the raw request payload using the shared secret, then compares that against the signature header the sender provided. The comparison uses PHP's `hash_equals()`, a [[fixture-shop/_glossary#Constant-Time Comparison|constant-time comparison]], so an attacker cannot learn the correct signature byte by byte from response timing."
}

